1. Executive Summary

    Project Name: MoreTea - A Pet Robot Assistant for Garage@EEE

    Version: [1.4]

    Status: Active Implementation

    The "One-Liner": A socially aware pet robot assistant that can sleep, wake, converse, guide tours, answer Garage@EEE questions, physically navigate indoor spaces safely, and switch between hosted LiveKit models and a laptop-hosted voice stack based on Ollama and OpenAI-compatible speech services.

2. The "Why" (Problem & Opportunity)

    Problem Statement: Garage@EEE is a student makerspace where many new users need repeated orientation, help finding resources, and answers to common process questions. Relying only on committee members does not scale and creates repetitive work.

    Target Audience: Students, visitors, and newcomers who want to understand Garage@EEE quickly and start building immediately.

    Value Proposition: Reduce repetitive onboarding effort, provide a memorable robot experience, and make the space easier to approach through a conversational assistant.

3. Goals & Success Metrics

    Primary Goal: MoreTea can wake on cue, answer Garage@EEE questions accurately, guide a user through a multi-stop tour, recover safely from robot navigation issues, and remain understandable to future developers.

    Success Metrics:
    - Can answer common Garage@EEE questions without obvious hallucinations.
    - Can run a full tour using configured stops and recover gracefully from failed stops.
    - Can stay asleep when not engaged and wake when addressed by name.
    - Can degrade into a stationary concierge when robot navigation is unavailable.
    - Can start with either hosted LiveKit inference or a self-hosted local STT-LLM-TTS stack through configuration only.
    - Can be extended by future developers without rebuilding the architecture from scratch.

4. Functional Requirements (User Stories)

ID	Feature	Priority	Description
FR-1	Autonomous Navigation	P0	Ability to navigate Garage@EEE stops with ROS 2 and Nav2.
FR-2	Tour Guiding	P0	Guide users through a multi-stop Garage tour with resumable progress.
FR-3	Garage QnA	P0	Answer follow-up questions about Garage@EEE, facilities, and programmes.
FR-4	Wake / Sleep Interaction	P1	Remain idle until addressed, then return to sleep after inactivity.
FR-5	Embodied Behaviour	P1	Use eyes and concise social behaviours to feel like a pet robot assistant.
FR-6	Failure Transparency	P1	Inform users when the robot pauses, replans, skips a stop, or cannot move.
FR-7	Personalisation	P2	Remember lightweight session facts such as user name or preferences.
FR-8	Degraded Operation	P1	Remain useful as a stationary concierge if ROS or Nav2 are unavailable.
FR-9	Startup Health Reporting	P1	Validate content and runtime readiness at startup and expose a structured health report.
FR-10	Configurable Model Stack	P1	Select between hosted LiveKit inference and self-hosted local STT, LLM, and TTS services through environment configuration.
FR-11	Hosted Fallback	P1	Fall back to hosted LiveKit models when local model services are unavailable and fallback is enabled.
FR-12	Documented Local Stack	P1	Provide a concrete, developer-friendly local setup path for the recommended Ollama plus Speaches stack.

5. Technical Constraints & Non-Functional Requirements

    Tech Stack: Python, LiveKit Agents, ROS 2 Humble, Nav2

    Architecture: Modular runtime, domain, service, and content split so future developers can extend the system safely.

    Knowledge Strategy: Garage@EEE knowledge remains prompt-injected at startup because the token footprint is small and low latency is preferred.

    Safety: Motion and degraded-mode decisions must be deterministic and not delegated purely to the LLM.

    Inference Strategy: The voice pipeline must support both cloud-backed and self-hosted STT-LLM-TTS providers, with local health checks before session startup.

    Interoperability: The system should remain evolvable toward a REST or API surface in a future milestone.

    Hardware Assumption: RESpeaker is used as a standard microphone only; wake behaviour is implemented in software at the agent runtime layer.

    Local Hardware Assumption: Development target for self-hosted inference is a laptop-class NVIDIA RTX 4060 GPU, prioritising low latency over maximum model size.

6. User Experience (UX) & Flow

    a. A user sees MoreTea idle in Garage@EEE.
    b. The user says "Hey MoreTea" or another configured wake phrase.
    c. MoreTea transitions from sleeping to attentive, greets the user, and answers initial questions or offers a tour.
    d. If the user starts a tour, MoreTea guides them stop by stop, narrates what each area is for, and reports any pauses or detours.
    e. The user can interrupt with follow-up questions, ask to go somewhere specific, or stop the robot.
    f. If navigation is unavailable, MoreTea remains a stationary concierge and explains that movement is disabled.
    g. If local model mode is enabled, MoreTea probes the local STT, LLM, and TTS services before startup and either uses them or falls back to hosted inference if configured.
    h. After inactivity, MoreTea returns to sleep and waits for the next interaction.

7. Implementation Notes

    Current implementation is organized into:
    - runtime session orchestration with startup health reporting and model-stack selection
    - agent classes for concierge and tour roles
    - domain state machines for interaction, safety, and tour state
    - services for navigation, engagement, affect, knowledge, telemetry, and memory
    - YAML-driven content for stops, FAQs, policies, and persona
    - environment-driven model configuration for local or hosted STT, LLM, and TTS

    Current delivery status:
    - the architectural refactor is complete
    - the software-first milestone is complete
    - startup health reporting, manual always-awake mode, and session memory are implemented
    - local self-hosted model configuration with hosted fallback is implemented
    - a concrete Ollama plus Speaches setup path is documented
    - hardware validation and real waypoint calibration remain the main open work

8. Milestones & Timeline

    Milestone 1: Architectural refactor to layered runtime, domain, service, and content model. Completed.

    Milestone 2: Stable navigation, retry or skip logic, and structured content configuration. In progress.

    Milestone 3: Sleep and wake interaction, affect mapping, and richer Garage assistant behaviour. In progress.

    Milestone 4: Self-hosted local model configuration and fallback path. Completed.

    Milestone 5: Concrete local setup documentation for Ollama plus Speaches. Completed.

    Milestone 6: Robot validation, latency tuning, and deployment hardening. Pending.
